y lost to bipolar affective disorder. Stearns was a fifty-two-year-old patient in a Galveston psychiatric hospital when Thomas Cole first met him in 1984. Over the course of a decade, Cole and Stearns slowly recovered the details of Stearns’s life before his slide into mental illness, writing a story that is more relevant today than ever. In this new edition, Cole fills in the gaps between the late 1990s and now, providing an update on the progress of civil rights in Houston and Stearns himself. He also reflects on his tumultuous and often painful collaboration with Stearns, challenging readers to be part of his journey to understand the struggles of a Black man’s complex life. At once poignant, tragic, and emotionally charged, No Color Is My Kind is essential reading as the current movement for racial reconciliation gathers momentum.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAfrican American civil rights workerszTexaszHoustonvBiography. 0aCivil rights movementszTexaszHoustonxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights workerszTexaszHoustonvBiography. 0aMentally illzTexaszHoustonvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aHouston, mental illness, desegregation, Texas history, race in America, civil rights movement, civil rights leader, desegregation movement, bipolar disorder, civil rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074527640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477323748423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477323748/original  a978-3-11-074527-6  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSH